{"title_page": "Hawes", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Distinguish|Hayes (disambiguation){{!}}Hayes|Hawnes}}\n{{Short description|Market town and civil parish in North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                 =England      \n|official_name           =Hawes\n|coordinates             = {{coord|54.304143|-2.1964180|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name       =Hawes.jpg\n|static_image_caption    =Market Place, Hawes\n|population              =1,137 \n|population_ref          =([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]])<ref name=\"2011 Census\"/>\n|shire_district          =[[Richmondshire]]\n|region                  =Yorkshire and the Humber\n|shire_county            =[[North Yorkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster=[[Richmond, North Yorkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Richmond]]\n|post_town               =HAWES\n|postcode_district       =DL8\n|postcode_area           =DL   \n|dial_code               =01969\n|os_grid_reference       =SD873898\n}}\n'''Hawes''' is a small [[market town]] and [[civil parish]] in Upper Wensleydale in the [[Richmondshire]] district of [[North Yorkshire]], England, that was granted its market charter in 1699. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] in the [[North Riding of Yorkshire]], Hawes is located at the head of [[Wensleydale]] in the [[Yorkshire Dales]]; the [[River Ure]] runs to the north of the town and is regarded as one of the [[honeypot (geography)|honeypot]] tourist attractions of the [[Yorkshire Dales National Park]]. It is known as the home to the Yorkshire Wensleydale Cheese.<ref name=\"Hawes - Yorkshire Dales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshire.com/places/yorkshire-dales/hawes|title=Hawes - Yorkshire Dales |publisher= Welcome to Yorkshire|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe population in 2011 was 887; the estimated population in 2016 was 893.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.info/php/uk-england-yorkshireandthehumber.php?cityid=E34003947|title=Hawes (North Yorkshire, Yorkshire and the Humber, United Kingdom) - Population Statistics, Charts, Map, Location, Weather and Web Information|website=www.citypopulation.info|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\nThe parish of Hawes also includes the neighbouring [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] of [[Gayle, North Yorkshire|Gayle]]. The population of the full parish was 1,137 in 2011<ref name=\"2011 Census\"/> and was estimated at 1,138 in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citypopulation.de/php/uk-parishes-yorkshireandthehumber.php?adm2id=E04007489|title=Hawes (Parish, United Kingdom) - Population Statistics, Charts, Map and Location|website=www.citypopulation.de|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Hawes is {{convert|31.2|mi}} west of the [[county town]] of [[Northallerton]]. The Wensleydale Creamery is a major producer of Yorkshire [[Wensleydale cheese]].\n\nDescribed by [[Reader's Digest]] as ''The Village That Refused to Die'', Hawes has a very active non-profit community group that seeks funding and uses the money to re-open keep community amenities that were closing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawescommunityoffice.co.uk/resources/Readers%20Digest%20Hawes.compressed.pdf|title=The Village that Refused to Die|work=Readers Digest|date=May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThere is no mention in the ''[[Domesday Book]]'' of a settlement where the current town is. There is little mention of the town until the 15th century when the population had risen enough for a [[chapel of ease]] to be built.<ref name=\"History\"/> The settlement was first recorded in 1307 as having a marketplace.<ref name=\"Hawes - Yorkshire Dales\"/>\n\nThe place's name is derived from the [[Old Norse]] word ''hals'', meaning \"neck\" or \"pass between mountains\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Watts|title=Cambridge Dictionary of English Place-names|page=288|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2011|isbn=978-0521168557}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=A.D. Mills|title=Dictionary of English Place-Names|page=233|publisher=Oxford Paperbacks|year=1998|isbn=978-0192800749}}</ref>\n\nThe town was granted a charter to hold markets by [[William III of England|King William III]] in 1699. It allowed for a weekly Tuesday market and two fairs a year. In 1887 an auction market was established in the town that held cattle sales fortnightly. In addition, five cattle fairs and three sheep fairs were held each year. Soon after, four cheese fairs spread over the year also became a regular event in the town.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=64744|title=History|accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulmers\">{{cite book|title=Bulmer's Topography, History and Directory (Private and Commercial) of North Yorkshire 1890|pages=343\u2013345|year=1890|publisher= S&N Publishing|isbn=1-86150-299-0}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Richmond to Lancaster Turnpike]] was diverted in 1795 and from then on, it passed through Hawes. The Wensleydale Railway reached Hawes in 1878.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.org/Wensleydale/LocalHistory.aspx|title=Wensleydale - Local History|first=|last=|publisher=Wensleydale|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> The village once had a [[Hawes railway station|railway station]] that was the terminus of the Hawes branch of the [[Midland Railway]] and an end-on terminus of the line from Northallerton from its opening in 1878 to its closure in April 1954. British Railways kept the line to Garsdale Junction open for passengers until 1959. The [[Wensleydale Railway#Line history|Wensleydale Railway Association]] which operates a heritage train<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydalerail.com/|title=Home - General |publisher=Wensleydale Railway|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> has plans to rebuild the railway from [[Northallerton]] (from its current western terminus at [[Redmire railway station|Redmire]]) to [[Garsdale railway station|Garsdale]] including re-opening the station in the village.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gleeson|first1=Janet|title=Heritage line unveils its station restoration plan|work=Darlington & Stockton Times|issue=46-2016|date=18 November 2016|page=3|issn=2040-3933}}</ref> [[Hawes railway station]] remains in its original site, now part of the [[Dales Countryside Museum]]. Since 2015, the building has been rented to a business operating a bike shop and later a cafe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshiredales.org.uk/living-and-working/other-services/press-office/news/recent/new-business-opens-in-dales-countryside-museum|title=New business opens in Dales Countryside Museum|publisher=Yorkshire Dales National Park Authority |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/14408332.New_cafe_opens_in_Dales_Countryside_Museum_in_Hawes/|title=New cafe opens in Dales Countryside Museum in Hawes|work=The Bolton News|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the past, a water powered mill operated at Gayle and in Hawes; the [[Gayle Mill, North Yorkshire]], for example, was built in 1784.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gaylemill.org.uk/about-gayle-mill|publisher=Gayle Mill Trust |title= About Gayle Mill|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The mills were used to grind corn, produce textiles (wool, cotton, linen, silk, flax), generate electricity or saw wood. Limestone was burnt in kilns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.org/Wensleydale/LocalHistory.aspx|title=Wensleydale - Local History|publisher=Wensleydale|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> In 1789, Gayle Mill adopted new technology, and became a mechanised sawmill powered by a double-vortex turbine. In 1919, part of the mill was hired to provide electricity to the area using turbines for the generator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaylemill.org.uk/our-heritage|title=Our Heritage|first=|last=|publisher=Gayle Mill Trust |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> The mill provided electricity for the village until 1948.<ref>{{NHLE||num=1132000 |desc=Gayle Mill - Hawes - North Yorkshire - England |date=25 March 1969 |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe town lies within the Richmond UK Parliament constituency. It also lies within the Upper Dales electoral division of North Yorkshire County Council and the Hawes & High Abbotside ward of Richmondshire District Council.<ref name=\"Survey\">{{Official website|http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/oswebsite/opendata/viewer/|name=Ordnance Survey Open Viewer}}</ref>\n\nThe civil parish shares a [[grouped parish council]] with the civil parish of [[High Abbotside]], known as Hawes & High Abbotside Parish Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmondshire.gov.uk/council-democracy/parish-and-town-councils|title=Parish and Town Councils|publisher=Richmondshire District Council|year=2014|accessdate=17 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819090519/http://www.richmondshire.gov.uk/council-democracy/parish-and-town-councils|archive-date=19 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> This is also an [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] with a combined population taken at the 2011 Census of 1,347.<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1237325133|title=Hawes and High Abbotside Ward (as of 2011)|accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Demography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n! colspan=\"11\"| Population<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit/10431761/cube/TOT_POP|title=Population at Cenuses|publisher=Vision of Britain|year=2009|accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"2001 Census\">{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadDatasetList.do?a=7&b=11124350&c=hawes&d=16&g=6454843&i=1001x1003x1032&m=0&r=1&s=1365169104935&enc=1&domainId=16|title=2001 UK Census|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics|year= 2002|accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"2011 Census\">{{NOMIS2011|id=1170217153|title=Hawes Parish|accessdate=17 March 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! Year !! 1881 !! 1891 !! 1901 !! 1911 !! 1921 !! 1931 !! 1951 !! 1961 !! 2001 !! 2011\n|-\n| Total || 1,890 || 1,615 || 1,595 || 1,518 || 1,430 || 1,404 || 1,196 || 1,137 || 1,127 || 1,137\n|}\n\n===2001 census===\nThe 2001 UK census showed that the population was split 50% male to 50% female. The religious constituency was made of 82% Christian, 1.5% Jewish and the rest stating no religion or not stating at all. The ethnic make-up was 97.9% White British, 1.3% White other, 0.5% Mixed ethnic and 0.3% Chinese. There were 601 dwellings.<ref name=\"2001 Census\"/>\n\n===2011 census===\nThe 2011 UK census showed that the population was split 50.1% male to 49.91% female. The religious constituency was made of 70.8% Christian, 3.8% Buddhist, 0.1% Muslim and the rest stating no religion or not stating at all. The ethnic make-up was 91.4% White British, 3.5% White Other, 0.3% Mixed Ethnic, 4.2% British Asian and 0.4% each British Black. There were 683 dwellings.<ref name=\"2011 Census\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nThe parish of Hawes covers the large areas of moorland on Dodd Fell, Snays Fell, Stags Fell and Widdale Fell and includes the River Ure tributaries of Widdale Beck and Gayle Beck. The latter flows through the town of Hawes. There are many abandoned lead mines, quarries and limekilns in the parish indicating its industrial past. A short distance from the town on Gayle Beck are the Aysgill Force waterfalls. The highest point in the parish is Great Knoutberry Hill at {{convert|2205|ft}}. The parish extends as far north as Hellgill Bridge along a narrow strip either side of the Ure.<ref name=\"Survey\"/>\n\nThe civil parish of Hawes also includes the neighbouring [[Hamlet (place)|hamlets]] of [[Gayle, North Yorkshire|Gayle]], [[Appersett]] and [[Burtersett]]. The [[A684 road]] from [[Sedbergh]] to [[Osmotherley, North Yorkshire|Osmotherley]] passes through the town and the [[B6255 road|B6255]] begins at the western edge of the town and links it to [[Ingleton, North Yorkshire|Ingleton]].<ref name=\"Survey\"/>\n\nThe M6 and the A1 to the east are under an hour away by car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairview-hawes.co.uk/local-attractions/|title=Hawes, Wensleydale, Yorkshire Dales, North Yorkshire - tourist information and attractions|website=www.fairview-hawes.co.uk|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Wensleydale Creamery - geograph.org.uk - 1343509.jpg|thumb|left|[[Wensleydale Creamery]]]]\nNow the largest company, with a staff of 224 (spring 2018) and visited by 250,000 people each year,<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/12/29/go-somewhere-cheese-gromit/|title=We'll go somewhere there's cheese, Gromit!|first=Jack|last=Torrance|date=29 December 2017|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2018|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> the [[Wensleydale Creamery]] Centre closed down in 1992; at that time, it was owned by Dairy Crest. Within six months, four ex-employees and a local businessman purchased the dormant creamery and reopened it.<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-4975544/Hawes-market-town-saved-itself.html|title=The town that saved itself by making services resident-run|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The operation moved to its current location in 2015 and still handcrafts<ref name=\"wensleydale.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.co.uk/about/|title=Yorkshire Wensleydale Cheese |publisher= Wensleydale Creamery|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> the eponymous cheese using traditional recipes following those first done by French monks in the 12th century. (Cheese has been made in this village since about 1150.)<ref name=\"wensleydale.co.uk\"/> Wensleydale Creamery has won many prestigious cheese awards, including ''Supreme Champion'' in 2018 for its new Yorkshire Cheddar at The Great Yorkshire Show\u2019s Cheese and Dairy Show. Yorkshire Wensleydale took the ''Reserve Supreme'' Cheese title. The company also received ten other trophies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondshiretoday.co.uk/wensleydale-creamery-wins-supreme-champion-cheese-great-yorkshire-show/|title=Wensleydale Creamery wins Supreme Champion Cheese at Great Yorkshire Show |work= Richmondshire Today|date=12 July 2018|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe cheeses produced by the Creamery applied for ''[[Geographical indications and traditional specialities (EU)|Protected Food Name Status]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wensleydale.co.uk/heritage-provenance|title=Cheese Awards|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> The application was successful and the protected geographical indication  certificate was received.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.co.uk/blog/the-wensleydale-creamery-unveils-seasonal-yorkshire-wensleydale-cranberries-packaging/|title=The Wensleydale Creamery unveils seasonal Yorkshire Wensleydale & Cranberries packaging |work= Wensleydale Blog|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> The term \"Yorkshire Wensleydale\" can only be used for cheese that is made in Wensleydale.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n[[File:Pub bullshead Hawes 177.jpg|thumb|A traditional pub with rooms to let in Hawes]]\n\nThe farms around Hawes raise sheep and cattle and grow meadow grass for hay and silage.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Tourism is important to Hawes; it is a market town with shops and accommodation for visitors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://visittheyorkshiredales.co.uk/hawes.php|title=Hawes in the Yorkshire Dales|first=Helen |last=Olney|website=visittheyorkshiredales.co.uk|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Over 40 farms in the general area supply the Creamery with milk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawescommunityoffice.co.uk/resources/Readers%20Digest%20Hawes.compressed.pdf|title=The Village that Refused to Die|work=Readers Digest|date=May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nA National Park Centre iLocal is located in the village, with a large parking area, beside the Countryside Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshiredales.org.uk/visit-the-dales/essential-information/tourist-information/hawes-national-park-centre|title=Hawes National Park Centre|publisher=Yorkshire Dales National Park Authority |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> Attractions<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.org/Wensleydale/OurTownHawes.aspx|title=Our Town Hawes|first=|publisher=Wensleydale|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> include the [[Dales Countryside Museum]], attached to the in the old Hawes railway station of the [[Wensleydale Railway]], nearby [[Hardraw Force]] waterfall, and the [[Buttertubs Pass]] which links Wensleydale to [[Swaledale]]. Hawes has a regular market on Tuesdays,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshiredales.org.uk/visit-the-dales/discover-the-dales/towns-and-villages/northern-dales-towns-and-villages/hawes|title=Hawes|publisher=Yorkshire Dales National Park Authority |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> as well as many shops, pubs and tearooms. Hawes is a centre for walking (hiking) the countryside and the [[Pennine Way]] passes through here. There is a [[youth hostel]] located on Lancaster Terrace at the western end of the town.<ref name=\"Survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yha.org.uk/hostel/hawes|title=Youth Hostel|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe bookseller Steve Bloom was based in Hawes.  His policy of charging a 50 pence entry fee to his shop made him nationally notorious.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jul/17/yorkshire-dales-bookseller-from-hell-quits-his-shop-hawes-steve-bloom-bloomindales|title=The end: Yorkshire Dales 'bookseller from hell' quits his shop}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jan/04/yorkshires-bookseller-from-hell-regrets-calling-customer-a-pain-in-the-arse|title=Yorkshire's 'bookseller from hell' regrets calling customer 'a pain in the arse'\n}}</ref>\n\nJust south of Hawes, the 18th century Gayle Mill is now a Grade II listed building, a scheduled monument.  In 2004, it was featured in [[BBC2]]'s [[Restoration (TV series)|Restoration]] programme.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> It came in the top three in the national finals. Restoration of the mill started in the same year and works to bring the site to operational standard took four years and cost over \u00a31m.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.darlingtonandstocktontimes.co.uk/news/2136871.joy_as_historic_mill_reopens_after_1m_restoration/ |title=Joy as historic mill reopens after \u00a31m restoration |work= Darlington and Stockton Times|date=21 March 2008 |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Although it was still open to visitors during the 2017 tourist season, the Gayle Mill Trust that operates the attraction was advised by the North of England Civic Trust in early 2018 that the mill would need to be closed. Work would be necessary to remedy problems discovered since the restoration in order to ensure safety and to comply with insurance regulations. The site was vacated in March 2018. The Civic Trust was hoping that the work could be completed in time to reopen it at Easter 2019. Fundraising was under way in summer 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondshiretoday.co.uk/gayle-mill-course-reopen-within-year-say-owners/|title=Gayle Mill on course to reopen within a year, say owners |work= Richmondshire Today|date=28 May 2018|publisher=|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Community amenities==\n\nHawes Community Primary School provides primary education for the town and nearby settlements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawes.n-yorks.sch.uk/|title=Primary School|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> It was established in 1878 and the school retains log books dating back to those dates. Pupils received secondary education at ''The Wensleydale School & Sixth Form'' in Leyburn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northyorks.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=18853&p=0|title=Secondary School Admissions \u2013 Northallerton Area|publisher=North Yorkshire County Council|year=2013|accessdate=26 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121004145628/http://www.northyorks.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=18853&p=0|archivedate=4 October 2012}}</ref> The Community School was rated as inadequate by an Ofsted report in late 2015; an action plan was established by North Yorkshire County Council to ensure improvement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/education/dales-primary-school-rated-as-inadequate-1-7695044|title=Dales primary school rated as \u2018inadequate\u2019|work=Yorkshire Post|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> In spring 2018, the school had 114 students.<ref name=\"YCAT-Hawes\">{{cite web |title=Hawes - Yorkshire Collaborative Academy Trust |url=http://ycatschools.co.uk/our-schools/hawes/ |website=Yorkshire Collaborative Academy Trust |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref> The closest secondary school is 17 miles from the village.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5094591/Hawes-market-town-refused-die.html|title=Why Hawes is the market town that refused to die|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe town has a retained fire station, which means that they are crewed by firefighters who provide on-call cover from home or their place of work.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our fire stations - North Yorkshire Fire & Rescue Service|url=http://www.northyorksfire.gov.uk/about-us/our-fire-stations|website=www.northyorksfire.gov.uk|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref> The station is operated by the [[North Yorkshire Fire and Rescue Service]].\n\nMedical care is available at the Hawes Surgery of The Health Centre. Three physicians serve this office and the one in [[Aysgarth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centraldalespractice.nhs.uk/Contact-Us|title=Get in touch |publisher= Central Dales Practice|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The nearest hospitals are Friary Hospital in Richmond ({{convert|23.4|km|order=flip}}) and [[Castleberg Hospital]] in Settle ({{convert|28.6|km|order=flip}}).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/li/hospitals.in.Hawes,%20North%20Yorkshire/|work=The Northern Echo|title=Hospitals in Hawes, North Yorkshire|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> \n \nOn weekends and bank holiday Mondays, the [[DalesBus]] travels among various villages,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dalesbus.org/uploads/1/1/3/9/113919127/dalesbus.pdf|format=PDF|title=DalesBus Summer Timetable|publisher=Dales Bus|accessdate=16 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716165748/https://www.dalesbus.org/uploads/1/1/3/9/113919127/dalesbus.pdf|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> including Hawes, from Easter Sunday until late summer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/why-the-value-of-rural-bus-services-cannot-be-overstated-in-our-national-parks-1-9084831|title=Why the value of rural bus services cannot be overstated in our National Parks|work=Yorkshire Post|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> Several other buses provide a year-round service stopping at Hawes and other villages in the area.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dalesbus.org/all-year-buses.html|title=All Year Buses|work=Dales Travel|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Saving village services===\nThe only petrol station at Hawes was expected to close in 2017 due to falling sales, and the next nearest re-fuelling station involved a {{convert|36|mi|0|adj=on}} round trip. A non-profit community group, the Upper Dales Community Partnership (UDCP), took a three-year lease on the station October 2017 after [[North Yorkshire County Council]] awarded a grant to the community grant. The Dale Head Garage is so remote that the town receives a \u00a30.05 rebate from the government on every litre of fuel sold. This benefit is passed on directly to consumers at the pump.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Copeland|first1=Alexa|title=Town takes over filling station to guarantee fuel|work=Darlington and Stockton Times|issue=41-2017|date=13 October 2017|page=1|issn=2040-3933}}</ref> A grant in May 2018 from the\nRichmondshire District Council\u2019s Economic Growth Fund enabled the petrol station to remain open 24 hours a day.<ref name=\"Round the clock fuel in Dales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/environment/round-the-clock-fuel-in-dales-1-9179729|title=Round the clock fuel in Dales|work=Yorkshire Post|date=26 May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> \n \nIn previous years, UDCP had also taken over the library and the post office. In February 2018 however, Royal Mail announced that the sorting department in the village would close. In addition to the loss of jobs, the plan would have meant that residents would be required to drive 30 minutes to Leyburn to pick up packages. Lobbying by village residents convinced the Post Office to cancel its plans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/our-region/west-yorkshire-and-the-dales/reprieve-for-hawes-sorting-office-as-post-office-says-no-to-royal-mail-closure-proposal-1-9035984|title=Reprieve for Hawes sorting office as Post Office says no to Royal Mail closure proposal|work=Yorkshire Post|date=14 February 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Partnership also started a bus service in 2011 when the previous service ceased operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawescommunityoffice.co.uk/resources/Readers%20Digest%20Hawes.compressed.pdf|title=The Village that Refused to Die|work=Readers Digest|date=May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> The Little White Bus has 11 vehicles and transports 60,000 visitors per year. After the police station was shut down, the constables were given a room in the community group's office which houses the Post Office and Library, and also offers free Wi-Fi, a coffee machine and a scanner/printer for use by residents. In 2018, the Partnership was considering a plan to start a Land Trust that would build four new houses and rent them to low-income families with children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawescommunityoffice.co.uk/resources/Readers%20Digest%20Hawes.compressed.pdf|title=The Village that Refused to Die|work=Readers Digest|date=May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nFormed over 20 years ago, the  Partnership has 25 paid staff and 60 volunteers (May 2018).<ref name=\"Round the clock fuel in Dales\"/> In 2017, the head of the non-profit group explained the original concept to ''[[The Times]]''. Unlike other communities which ask, \"Why isn't the government providing for us?\", the philosophy at Hawes has been, \"If you aren't going to provide for us we are going to provide it for ourselves\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5073199/Self-sufficient-Yorkshire-village-overtakes-petrol-station.html|title=Self-sufficient Yorkshire village takes over petrol station|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St Margaret's Church, Hawes - geograph.org.uk - 1599173.jpg|thumb|right|St Margaret's Church]]\nThe church in Hawes is dedicated to [[Margaret the Virgin|St Margaret of Antioch]]. The current building was rebuilt in 1850 on the site of the former [[chapel of ease]] and is a Grade II listed building.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1166758|desc=Church Of Saint Margaret Of Antioch|accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref> There were Wesleyan and Congregational chapels in the village as well as the [[Sandemanians]] and a Friends Meeting House.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref name=\"Bulmers\"/>\n[[File:St margs Hawes glass dd 9212.jpg|thumb|left|One of several stained glass windows at St Margaret's]]\nThe Methodist Church in Hawes was built in 1856 and was part of the Wensleydale Circuit. It closed in 2015, was sold in early 2017, and placed again on the market in early 2018.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondshiretoday.co.uk/owners-former-hawes-church-deny-fast-buck-claim/|\nwork=Richmond Today|title=Owners of former Hawes church deny \"fast buck\" claim|\naccessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> Worshippers can attend the chapel in nearby Gayle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydalesmeth.org.uk/hawes.htm|title=Methodist Church|accessdate=5 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113044006/http://www.nydalesmeth.org.uk/hawes.htm|archivedate=13 January 2014}}</ref> \n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Clarke's Monthly Advertising Journal, for Leyburn, Middleham, Askrigg, Hawes, Sedbergh, and Kirkby Stephen, also for Dent and Swaledale''. Hawes: Fletcher Clarke\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Hawes}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n\n{{North Yorkshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hawes| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Market towns in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Wensleydale]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses2}}\n{{Distinguish|Hayes (disambiguation){{!}}Hayes|Hawnes}}\n{{Short description|Market town and civil parish in North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                 =England      \n|official_name           =Hawes\n|coordinates             = {{coord|54.304143|-2.1964180|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name       =Hawes.jpg\n|static_image_caption    =Market Place, Hawes\n|population              =1,137 \n|population_ref          =([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]])<ref name=\"2011 Census\"/>\n|shire_district          =[[Richmondshire]]\n|region                  =Yorkshire and the Humber\n|shire_county            =[[North Yorkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster=[[Richmond, North Yorkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Richmond]]\n|post_town               =HAWES\n|postcode_district       =DL8\n|postcode_area           =DL   \n|dial_code               =01969\n|os_grid_reference       =SD873898\n}}\n'''Hawes''' is a small [[market town]] and [[civil parish]] in Upper Wensleydale in the [[Richmondshire]] district of [[North Yorkshire]], England, that was granted its market charter in 1699. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] in the [[North Riding of Yorkshire]], Hawes is located at the head of [[Wensleydale]] in the [[Yorkshire Dales]]; the [[River Ure]] runs to the north of the town and is regarded as one of the [[honeypot (geography)|honeypot]] tourist attractions of the [[Yorkshire Dales National Park]]. It is known as the home to the Yorkshire Wensleydale Cheese.<ref name=\"Hawes - Yorkshire Dales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshire.com/places/yorkshire-dales/hawes|title=Hawes - Yorkshire Dales |publisher= Welcome to Yorkshire|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe population in 2011 was 887; the estimated population in 2016 was 893.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.info/php/uk-england-yorkshireandthehumber.php?cityid=E34003947|title=Hawes (North Yorkshire, Yorkshire and the Humber, United Kingdom) - Population Statistics, Charts, Map, Location, Weather and Web Information|website=www.citypopulation.info|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\nThe parish of Hawes also includes the neighbouring [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] of [[Gayle, North Yorkshire|Gayle]]. The population of the full parish was 1,137 in 2011<ref name=\"2011 Census\"/> and was estimated at 1,138 in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citypopulation.de/php/uk-parishes-yorkshireandthehumber.php?adm2id=E04007489|title=Hawes (Parish, United Kingdom) - Population Statistics, Charts, Map and Location|website=www.citypopulation.de|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Hawes is {{convert|31.2|mi}} west of the [[county town]] of [[Northallerton]]. The Wensleydale Creamery is a major producer of Yorkshire [[Wensleydale cheese]].\n\nDescribed by [[Reader's Digest]] as ''The Village That Refused to Die'', Hawes has a very active non-profit community group that seeks funding and uses the money to re-open keep community amenities that were closing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawescommunityoffice.co.uk/resources/Readers%20Digest%20Hawes.compressed.pdf|title=The Village that Refused to Die|work=Readers Digest|date=May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThere is no mention in the ''[[Domesday Book]]'' of a settlement where the current town is. There is little mention of the town until the 15th century when the population had risen enough for a [[chapel of ease]] to be built.<ref name=\"History\"/> The settlement was first recorded in 1307 as having a marketplace.<ref name=\"Hawes - Yorkshire Dales\"/>\n\nThe place's name is derived from the [[Old Norse]] word ''hals'', meaning \"neck\" or \"pass between mountains\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Watts|title=Cambridge Dictionary of English Place-names|page=288|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2011|isbn=978-0521168557}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=A.D. Mills|title=Dictionary of English Place-Names|page=233|publisher=Oxford Paperbacks|year=1998|isbn=978-0192800749}}</ref>\n\nThe town was granted a charter to hold markets by [[William III of England|King William III]] in 1699. It allowed for a weekly Tuesday market and two fairs a year. In 1887 an auction market was established in the town that held cattle sales fortnightly. In addition, five cattle fairs and three sheep fairs were held each year. Soon after, four cheese fairs spread over the year also became a regular event in the town.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=64744|title=History|accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulmers\">{{cite book|title=Bulmer's Topography, History and Directory (Private and Commercial) of North Yorkshire 1890|pages=343\u2013345|year=1890|publisher= S&N Publishing|isbn=1-86150-299-0}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Richmond to Lancaster Turnpike]] was diverted in 1795 and from then on, it passed through Hawes. The Wensleydale Railway reached Hawes in 1878.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.org/Wensleydale/LocalHistory.aspx|title=Wensleydale - Local History|first=|last=|publisher=Wensleydale|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> The village once had a [[Hawes railway station|railway station]] that was the terminus of the Hawes branch of the [[Midland Railway]] and an end-on terminus of the line from Northallerton from its opening in 1878 to its closure in April 1954. British Railways kept the line to Garsdale Junction open for passengers until 1959. The [[Wensleydale Railway#Line history|Wensleydale Railway Association]] which operates a heritage train<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydalerail.com/|title=Home - General |publisher=Wensleydale Railway|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> has plans to rebuild the railway from [[Northallerton]] (from its current western terminus at [[Redmire railway station|Redmire]]) to [[Garsdale railway station|Garsdale]] including re-opening the station in the village.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gleeson|first1=Janet|title=Heritage line unveils its station restoration plan|work=Darlington & Stockton Times|issue=46-2016|date=18 November 2016|page=3|issn=2040-3933}}</ref> [[Hawes railway station]] remains in its original site, now part of the [[Dales Countryside Museum]]. Since 2015, the building has been rented to a business operating a bike shop and later a cafe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshiredales.org.uk/living-and-working/other-services/press-office/news/recent/new-business-opens-in-dales-countryside-museum|title=New business opens in Dales Countryside Museum|publisher=Yorkshire Dales National Park Authority |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/14408332.New_cafe_opens_in_Dales_Countryside_Museum_in_Hawes/|title=New cafe opens in Dales Countryside Museum in Hawes|work=The Bolton News|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the past, a water powered mill operated at Gayle and in Hawes; the [[Gayle Mill, North Yorkshire]], for example, was built in 1784.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gaylemill.org.uk/about-gayle-mill|publisher=Gayle Mill Trust |title= About Gayle Mill|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The mills were used to grind corn, produce textiles (wool, cotton, linen, silk, flax), generate electricity or saw wood. Limestone was burnt in kilns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.org/Wensleydale/LocalHistory.aspx|title=Wensleydale - Local History|publisher=Wensleydale|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> In 1789, Gayle Mill adopted new technology, and became a mechanised sawmill powered by a double-vortex turbine. In 1919, part of the mill was hired to provide electricity to the area using turbines for the generator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaylemill.org.uk/our-heritage|title=Our Heritage|first=|last=|publisher=Gayle Mill Trust |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> The mill provided electricity for the village until 1948.<ref>{{NHLE||num=1132000 |desc=Gayle Mill - Hawes - North Yorkshire - England |date=25 March 1969 |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe town lies within the Richmond UK Parliament constituency. It also lies within the Upper Dales electoral division of North Yorkshire County Council and the Hawes & High Abbotside ward of Richmondshire District Council.<ref name=\"Survey\">{{Official website|http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/oswebsite/opendata/viewer/|name=Ordnance Survey Open Viewer}}</ref>\n\nThe civil parish shares a [[grouped parish council]] with the civil parish of [[High Abbotside]], known as Hawes & High Abbotside Parish Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richmondshire.gov.uk/council-democracy/parish-and-town-councils|title=Parish and Town Councils|publisher=Richmondshire District Council|year=2014|accessdate=17 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819090519/http://www.richmondshire.gov.uk/council-democracy/parish-and-town-councils|archive-date=19 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> This is also an [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] with a combined population taken at the 2011 Census of 1,347.<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=1237325133|title=Hawes and High Abbotside Ward (as of 2011)|accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Demography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n! colspan=\"11\"| Population<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit/10431761/cube/TOT_POP|title=Population at Cenuses|publisher=Vision of Britain|year=2009|accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"2001 Census\">{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadDatasetList.do?a=7&b=11124350&c=hawes&d=16&g=6454843&i=1001x1003x1032&m=0&r=1&s=1365169104935&enc=1&domainId=16|title=2001 UK Census|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics|year= 2002|accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"2011 Census\">{{NOMIS2011|id=1170217153|title=Hawes Parish|accessdate=17 March 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! Year !! 1881 !! 1891 !! 1901 !! 1911 !! 1921 !! 1931 !! 1951 !! 1961 !! 2001 !! 2011\n|-\n| Total || 1,890 || 1,615 || 1,595 || 1,518 || 1,430 || 1,404 || 1,196 || 1,137 || 1,127 || 1,137\n|}\n\n===2001 census===\nThe 2001 UK census showed that the population was split 50% male to 50% female. The religious constituency was made of 82% Christian, 1.5% Jewish and the rest stating no religion or not stating at all. The ethnic make-up was 97.9% White British, 1.3% White other, 0.5% Mixed ethnic and 0.3% Chinese. There were 601 dwellings.<ref name=\"2001 Census\"/>\n\n===2011 census===\nThe 2011 UK census showed that the population was split 50.1% male to 49.91% female. The religious constituency was made of 70.8% Christian, 3.8% Buddhist, 0.1% Muslim and the rest stating no religion or not stating at all. The ethnic make-up was 91.4% White British, 3.5% White Other, 0.3% Mixed Ethnic, 4.2% British Asian and 0.4% each British Black. There were 683 dwellings.<ref name=\"2011 Census\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nThe parish of Hawes covers the large areas of moorland on Dodd Fell, Snays Fell, Stags Fell and Widdale Fell and includes the River Ure tributaries of Widdale Beck and Gayle Beck. The latter flows through the town of Hawes. There are many abandoned lead mines, quarries and limekilns in the parish indicating its industrial past. A short distance from the town on Gayle Beck are the Aysgill Force waterfalls. The highest point in the parish is Great Knoutberry Hill at {{convert|2205|ft}}. The parish extends as far north as Hellgill Bridge along a narrow strip either side of the Ure.<ref name=\"Survey\"/>\n\nThe civil parish of Hawes also includes the neighbouring [[Hamlet (place)|hamlets]] of [[Gayle, North Yorkshire|Gayle]], [[Appersett]] and [[Burtersett]]. The [[A684 road]] from [[Sedbergh]] to [[Osmotherley, North Yorkshire|Osmotherley]] passes through the town and the [[B6255 road|B6255]] begins at the western edge of the town and links it to [[Ingleton, North Yorkshire|Ingleton]].<ref name=\"Survey\"/>\n\nThe M6 and the A1 to the east are under an hour away by car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fairview-hawes.co.uk/local-attractions/|title=Hawes, Wensleydale, Yorkshire Dales, North Yorkshire - tourist information and attractions|website=www.fairview-hawes.co.uk|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Wensleydale Creamery - geograph.org.uk - 1343509.jpg|thumb|left|[[Wensleydale Creamery]]]]\nNow the largest company, with a staff of 224 (spring 2018) and visited by 250,000 people each year,<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/12/29/go-somewhere-cheese-gromit/|title=We'll go somewhere there's cheese, Gromit!|first=Jack|last=Torrance|date=29 December 2017|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2018|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> the [[Wensleydale Creamery]] Centre closed down in 1992; at that time, it was owned by Dairy Crest. Within six months, four ex-employees and a local businessman purchased the dormant creamery and reopened it.<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-4975544/Hawes-market-town-saved-itself.html|title=The town that saved itself by making services resident-run|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The operation moved to its current location in 2015 and still handcrafts<ref name=\"wensleydale.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.co.uk/about/|title=Yorkshire Wensleydale Cheese |publisher= Wensleydale Creamery|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> the eponymous cheese using traditional recipes following those first done by French monks in the 12th century. (Cheese has been made in this village since about 1150.)<ref name=\"wensleydale.co.uk\"/> Wensleydale Creamery has won many prestigious cheese awards, including ''Supreme Champion'' in 2018 for its new Yorkshire Cheddar at The Great Yorkshire Show\u2019s Cheese and Dairy Show. Yorkshire Wensleydale took the ''Reserve Supreme'' Cheese title. The company also received ten other trophies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondshiretoday.co.uk/wensleydale-creamery-wins-supreme-champion-cheese-great-yorkshire-show/|title=Wensleydale Creamery wins Supreme Champion Cheese at Great Yorkshire Show |work= Richmondshire Today|date=12 July 2018|publisher=|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe cheeses produced by the Creamery applied for ''[[Geographical indications and traditional specialities (EU)|Protected Food Name Status]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wensleydale.co.uk/heritage-provenance|title=Cheese Awards|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> The application was successful and the protected geographical indication  certificate was received.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.co.uk/blog/the-wensleydale-creamery-unveils-seasonal-yorkshire-wensleydale-cranberries-packaging/|title=The Wensleydale Creamery unveils seasonal Yorkshire Wensleydale & Cranberries packaging |work= Wensleydale Blog|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> The term \"Yorkshire Wensleydale\" can only be used for cheese that is made in Wensleydale.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n[[File:Pub bullshead Hawes 177.jpg|thumb|A traditional pub with rooms to let in Hawes]]\n\nThe farms around Hawes raise sheep and cattle and grow meadow grass for hay and silage.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Tourism is important to Hawes; it is a market town with shops and accommodation for visitors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://visittheyorkshiredales.co.uk/hawes.php|title=Hawes in the Yorkshire Dales|first=Helen |last=Olney|website=visittheyorkshiredales.co.uk|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Over 40 farms in the general area supply the Creamery with milk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawescommunityoffice.co.uk/resources/Readers%20Digest%20Hawes.compressed.pdf|title=The Village that Refused to Die|work=Readers Digest|date=May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nA National Park Centre iLocal is located in the village, with a large parking area, beside the Countryside Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshiredales.org.uk/visit-the-dales/essential-information/tourist-information/hawes-national-park-centre|title=Hawes National Park Centre|publisher=Yorkshire Dales National Park Authority |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> Attractions<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wensleydale.org/Wensleydale/OurTownHawes.aspx|title=Our Town Hawes|first=|publisher=Wensleydale|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> include the [[Dales Countryside Museum]], attached to the in the old Hawes railway station of the [[Wensleydale Railway]], nearby [[Hardraw Force]] waterfall, and the [[Buttertubs Pass]] which links Wensleydale to [[Swaledale]]. Hawes has a regular market on Tuesdays,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkshiredales.org.uk/visit-the-dales/discover-the-dales/towns-and-villages/northern-dales-towns-and-villages/hawes|title=Hawes|publisher=Yorkshire Dales National Park Authority |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> as well as many shops, pubs and tearooms. Hawes is a centre for walking (hiking) the countryside and the [[Pennine Way]] passes through here. There is a [[youth hostel]] located on Lancaster Terrace at the western end of the town.<ref name=\"Survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yha.org.uk/hostel/hawes|title=Youth Hostel|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe bookseller Steve Bloom was based in Hawes.  His policy of charging a 50 pence entry fee to his shop made him nationally notorious.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jul/17/yorkshire-dales-bookseller-from-hell-quits-his-shop-hawes-steve-bloom-bloomindales|title=The end: Yorkshire Dales 'bookseller from hell' quits his shop}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jan/04/yorkshires-bookseller-from-hell-regrets-calling-customer-a-pain-in-the-arse|title=Yorkshire's 'bookseller from hell' regrets calling customer 'a pain in the arse'\n}}</ref>\n\nJust south of Hawes, the 18th century Gayle Mill is now a Grade II listed building, a scheduled monument.  In 2004, it was featured in [[BBC2]]'s [[Restoration (TV series)|Restoration]] programme.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> It came in the top three in the national finals. Restoration of the mill started in the same year and works to bring the site to operational standard took four years and cost over \u00a31m.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.darlingtonandstocktontimes.co.uk/news/2136871.joy_as_historic_mill_reopens_after_1m_restoration/ |title=Joy as historic mill reopens after \u00a31m restoration |work= Darlington and Stockton Times|date=21 March 2008 |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Although it was still open to visitors during the 2017 tourist season, the Gayle Mill Trust that operates the attraction was advised by the North of England Civic Trust in early 2018 that the mill would need to be closed. Work would be necessary to remedy problems discovered since the restoration in order to ensure safety and to comply with insurance regulations. The site was vacated in March 2018. The Civic Trust was hoping that the work could be completed in time to reopen it at Easter 2019. Fundraising was under way in summer 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondshiretoday.co.uk/gayle-mill-course-reopen-within-year-say-owners/|title=Gayle Mill on course to reopen within a year, say owners |work= Richmondshire Today|date=28 May 2018|publisher=|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Community amenities==\n\nHawes Community Primary School provides primary education for the town and nearby settlements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawes.n-yorks.sch.uk/|title=Primary School|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> It was established in 1878 and the school retains log books dating back to those dates. Pupils received secondary education at ''The Wensleydale School & Sixth Form'' in Leyburn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northyorks.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=18853&p=0|title=Secondary School Admissions \u2013 Northallerton Area|publisher=North Yorkshire County Council|year=2013|accessdate=26 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121004145628/http://www.northyorks.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=18853&p=0|archivedate=4 October 2012}}</ref> The Community School was rated as inadequate by an Ofsted report in late 2015; an action plan was established by North Yorkshire County Council to ensure improvement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/education/dales-primary-school-rated-as-inadequate-1-7695044|title=Dales primary school rated as \u2018inadequate\u2019|work=Yorkshire Post|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> In spring 2018, the school had 114 students.<ref name=\"YCAT-Hawes\">{{cite web |title=Hawes - Yorkshire Collaborative Academy Trust |url=http://ycatschools.co.uk/our-schools/hawes/ |website=Yorkshire Collaborative Academy Trust |accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref> The closest secondary school is 17 miles from the village.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5094591/Hawes-market-town-refused-die.html|title=Why Hawes is the market town that refused to die|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe town has a retained fire station, which means that they are crewed by firefighters who provide on-call cover from home or their place of work.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our fire stations - North Yorkshire Fire & Rescue Service|url=http://www.northyorksfire.gov.uk/about-us/our-fire-stations|website=www.northyorksfire.gov.uk|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref> The station is operated by the [[North Yorkshire Fire and Rescue Service]].\n\nMedical care is available at the Hawes Surgery of The Health Centre. Three physicians serve this office and the one in [[Aysgarth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centraldalespractice.nhs.uk/Contact-Us|title=Get in touch |publisher= Central Dales Practice|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The nearest hospitals are Friary Hospital in Richmond ({{convert|23.4|km|order=flip}}) and [[Castleberg Hospital]] in Settle ({{convert|28.6|km|order=flip}}).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/li/hospitals.in.Hawes,%20North%20Yorkshire/|work=The Northern Echo|title=Hospitals in Hawes, North Yorkshire|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> \n \nOn weekends and bank holiday Mondays, the [[DalesBus]] travels among various villages,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dalesbus.org/uploads/1/1/3/9/113919127/dalesbus.pdf|format=PDF|title=DalesBus Summer Timetable|publisher=Dales Bus|accessdate=16 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716165748/https://www.dalesbus.org/uploads/1/1/3/9/113919127/dalesbus.pdf|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> including Hawes, from Easter Sunday until late summer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/why-the-value-of-rural-bus-services-cannot-be-overstated-in-our-national-parks-1-9084831|title=Why the value of rural bus services cannot be overstated in our National Parks|work=Yorkshire Post|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref> Several other buses provide a year-round service stopping at Hawes and other villages in the area.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dalesbus.org/all-year-buses.html|title=All Year Buses|work=Dales Travel|accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Saving village services===\nThe only petrol station at Hawes was expected to close in 2017 due to falling sales, and the next nearest re-fuelling station involved a {{convert|36|mi|0|adj=on}} round trip. A non-profit community group, the Upper Dales Community Partnership (UDCP), took a three-year lease on the station October 2017 after [[North Yorkshire County Council]] awarded a grant to the community grant. The Dale Head Garage is so remote that the town receives a \u00a30.05 rebate from the government on every litre of fuel sold. This benefit is passed on directly to consumers at the pump.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Copeland|first1=Alexa|title=Town takes over filling station to guarantee fuel|work=Darlington and Stockton Times|issue=41-2017|date=13 October 2017|page=1|issn=2040-3933}}</ref> A grant in May 2018 from the\nRichmondshire District Council\u2019s Economic Growth Fund enabled the petrol station to remain open 24 hours a day.<ref name=\"Round the clock fuel in Dales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/environment/round-the-clock-fuel-in-dales-1-9179729|title=Round the clock fuel in Dales|work=Yorkshire Post|date=26 May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> \n \nIn previous years, UDCP had also taken over the library and the post office. In February 2018 however, Royal Mail announced that the sorting department in the village would close. In addition to the loss of jobs, the plan would have meant that residents would be required to drive 30 minutes to Leyburn to pick up packages. Lobbying by village residents convinced the Post Office to cancel its plans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/our-region/west-yorkshire-and-the-dales/reprieve-for-hawes-sorting-office-as-post-office-says-no-to-royal-mail-closure-proposal-1-9035984|title=Reprieve for Hawes sorting office as Post Office says no to Royal Mail closure proposal|work=Yorkshire Post|date=14 February 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Partnership also started a bus service in 2011 when the previous service ceased operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawescommunityoffice.co.uk/resources/Readers%20Digest%20Hawes.compressed.pdf|title=The Village that Refused to Die|work=Readers Digest|date=May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> The Little White Bus has 11 vehicles and transports 60,000 visitors per year. After the police station was shut down, the constables were given a room in the community group's office which houses the Post Office and Library, and also offers free Wi-Fi, a coffee machine and a scanner/printer for use by residents. In 2018, the Partnership was considering a plan to start a Land Trust that would build four new houses and rent them to low-income families with children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawescommunityoffice.co.uk/resources/Readers%20Digest%20Hawes.compressed.pdf|title=The Village that Refused to Die|work=Readers Digest|date=May 2018|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nFormed over 20 years ago, the  Partnership has 25 paid staff and 60 volunteers (May 2018).<ref name=\"Round the clock fuel in Dales\"/> In 2017, the head of the non-profit group explained the original concept to ''[[The Times]]''. Unlike other communities which ask, \"Why isn't the government providing for us?\", the philosophy at Hawes has been, \"If you aren't going to provide for us we are going to provide it for ourselves\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5073199/Self-sufficient-Yorkshire-village-overtakes-petrol-station.html|title=Self-sufficient Yorkshire village takes over petrol station|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St Margaret's Church, Hawes - geograph.org.uk - 1599173.jpg|thumb|right|St Margaret's Church]]\nThe church in Hawes is dedicated to [[Margaret the Virgin|St Margaret of Antioch]]. The current building was rebuilt in 1850 on the site of the former [[chapel of ease]] and is a Grade II listed building.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1166758|desc=Church Of Saint Margaret Of Antioch|accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref> There were Wesleyan and Congregational chapels in the village as well as the [[Sandemanians]] and a Friends Meeting House.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref name=\"Bulmers\"/>\n[[File:St margs Hawes glass dd 9212.jpg|thumb|left|One of several stained glass windows at St Margaret's]]\nThe Methodist Church in Hawes was built in 1856 and was part of the Wensleydale Circuit. It closed in 2015, was sold in early 2017, and placed again on the market in early 2018.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmondshiretoday.co.uk/owners-former-hawes-church-deny-fast-buck-claim/|\nwork=Richmond Today|title=Owners of former Hawes church deny \"fast buck\" claim|\naccessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> Worshippers can attend the chapel in nearby Gayle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydalesmeth.org.uk/hawes.htm|title=Methodist Church|accessdate=5 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113044006/http://www.nydalesmeth.org.uk/hawes.htm|archivedate=13 January 2014}}</ref> \n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Clarke's Monthly Advertising Journal, for Leyburn, Middleham, Askrigg, Hawes, Sedbergh, and Kirkby Stephen, also for Dent and Swaledale''. Hawes: Fletcher Clarke\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Hawes}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n\n{{North Yorkshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hawes| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Market towns in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Wensleydale]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawes"}
